Database Migrations
===================

This directory contains Alembic migration scripts for the marketing campaign
builder database.

Local development
-----------------
The API and Worker processes automatically apply all pending migrations at
startup when ``DB_AUTH_MODE=local`` (the default).  No separate migration step
is required for day-to-day development.

    # Start the local stack — migrations run automatically on API startup
    podman-compose up

Cloud deployments (azure mode)
-------------------------------
In cloud deployments (``DB_AUTH_MODE=azure``), schema mutations are
**not** performed by the API or Worker at startup.  Instead, schema
changes are owned by the dedicated **migration job** that runs before the
new application revisions are activated.

The migration job is an Azure Container Apps Job
(``caj-<env>-migration``) that runs::

    python -m backend.apps.migrate.main

It uses its own user-assigned managed identity which has been granted
DDL permissions on the database, keeping those elevated privileges out of
the long-running API and Worker identities.

Rollout order
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Follow this order for every release that includes schema changes:

1. Build and push the new container image to the Azure Container Registry.
2. Trigger ``caj-<env>-migration`` via the Azure portal, CLI, or CI
   pipeline and wait for it to complete successfully (exit code 0).
3. Deploy the updated API revision.
4. Deploy the updated Worker revision.

The API and Worker will refuse to start if the database schema does not
match the expected head revision.  This prevents the application from
running against an incompatible schema.

Failure handling
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
If the migration job exits non-zero:

- The existing API and Worker revisions continue running unaffected
  (they remain on the old revision and old schema).
- Inspect the job execution logs in Azure Log Analytics / the Container
  Apps log stream.
- Fix the migration script, build a new image, and re-trigger the job.
- Do **not** activate new API/Worker revisions until the job succeeds.

Writing new migrations
----------------------
Generate a new migration with::

    # From the backend/ directory
    alembic revision --autogenerate -m "describe your change"

Review the generated file in ``versions/`` before committing.  Each
migration should be idempotent where possible (use ``IF NOT EXISTS`` /
``IF EXISTS`` guards in raw SQL).
